up|42|NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The bidding was fine. I will discuss my options in a moment. Jacquie should bid 4@H. I am just saying she should not be surprised if it goes down. In general the @SK would bid much more useful as the @DK or the @CK.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What I should bid. My hand actually does meet the rule of 20 and could be opened 1@S. However, in 3rd seat, preempting is particularly useful since the other 2 players passed, and I only have 10 HCP, it is very likely that Liza has a good hand. So in 3rd seat, on borderline hands where you might open 1 or 2, opening 2 is usually a better tactic than opening 1. Even in 4th seat, I would open this hand 2@S.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Opening 2@S in 4th seat is a whole different matter. It is not exactly a preempt. It shows a minimish opening hand (up to 13 or 14 HCP) with a 6 card suit. The idea is game is unlikely unless we have a nice fit. So opening 2@S is both an obstructive bid for the opponents and a descriptive bid for us you don't want to do it with too weak a hand or too strong a hand. But a minimish hand with a 6 card suit is a good candidate for opening 2 in 4th seat.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What I would do with my hand in 1st or 2nd seat? In 1st seat I would still probably preempt and open 2@S. The reason is, first seat is the 2nd most effective seat for preempting after 3rd seat. 2 of the opponents have not yet bid, and only my partner has not yet bid, so it is more likely the oppose have the strength than your side does. You want to preempt when your side is weaker than the opposition. |
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you could know your partner has a strong hand, you would not want to preempt, as that makes it harder when the hand is yours. But in 1st seat, the odds still favor that, when you have a weakish hand, their side is more likely to be stronger. In 2nd seat, however, that is no longer true. You have one passing opponent who is known to be relatively weak. Therefore, it is more likely partner could have a good hand. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I am not saying don't preempt in 2nd seat. You absolutely should. But when you have a marginal preempt, then in 2nd seat it might be better to not preempt if you have another good choice. So in 2nd seat, I would open my hand 1@S.|
